DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260417T183000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260417T203000
SUMMARY:All About the Historic Beaches! (EVENING EXTENDED TOUR)
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n[torontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmai
 l.com%2A%2A/)\n**for more information or for signing up!\\*\\***\n\\*\\* *
 *Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket price when booking your space f
 or this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n[torontohis
 torywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com%2A%2A/)\n\nThe a
 rea was first settled in 1794 by the Ashbridge family\, whose name is reme
 mbered by the nearby bay and park. Their homestead on Queen Street East wa
 s well to the west of the area currently identified as the Beaches. A late
 r generation of the Ashbridge family rebuilt the family home in 1854 and c
 an be seen on Queen Street East opposite the TTC barns near Kingston Road.
 \n\nThe Beaches remained a sparely settled community until the end of the 
 19th century when extension of the Grand Truck Railway\, the draining of t
 he northern parts of Ashbridges Bay\, and the construction of street car t
 racks on Queen Street and Kingston Road\, opened the area to settlement.\n
 \nFrom Sunnyside Amusement Park built in 1922 to Scarboro Beach built in 1
 906\, it seemed that Toronto cornered the market on summertime chills and 
 thrills.\n\nWe had 5 major amusement parks along our waterfront\, and two 
 smaller parks\, Victoria Park and Munro Park\, virtually unknown to Toront
 onians today\, but extremely popular summertime places\, years ago as plea
 sure parks.\n\nThis walking tour is for all walking levels and fitness ski
 lls. Please dress for the season and bring water. And remember to bring yo
 ur love of history.\n\nIt begins outside the Beaches Branch of the Toronto
  Public Library at Queen Street East\, and Lee Avenue adjacent to Kew Gard
 ens. The tour ends at the Neville Park Queen Street Streetcar Loop.\n\nThi
 s tour has a ticket price of $15.00 per person.\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: P
 lease e-transfer the ticket price when booking your space for this tour! Y
 ou can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n[torontohistorywalks@gmail
 .com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com%2A%2A/)
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/313367
 250/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260215T133734Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260215T133734Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_313004899@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T140000
SUMMARY:Toronto's Darkest Secrets! The Original Tour (RETURN FOR 2026)
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**[torontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gm
 ail.com/)**\n**for more information or for signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* *
 *Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket amount when booking your space 
 for this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**[toronto
 historywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com/)**\n\nThis t
 our was one of the original 5 tours that started it all back in 2019. Hear
  about the stories that still haunt Toronto. From the murder of a shoeshin
 e boy to the place where the gallows were constructed. Stories of Toronto'
 s hidden history.\n\nSo you want to hear all about Toronto's darkest momen
 ts\, do you?\n\nToronto has a rich and varied history\, we all know that\,
  or we should.\n\nLet's explore new and old stories of Toronto's darkest h
 istorical moments\, a new crop of dark secrets\, and a few of the old stor
 ies to make the blood run cold.\n\nAnd these secrets will be revealed in t
 ime. That's all I'm saying. I guess you'll have to sign up and commit to t
 he true darkness hidden in the human spirit.\n\nThis horrific walking tour
  is for all levels and walkers.\n\nThe tour begins on the site of the old 
 Ford Hotel at the northeast corner of Dundas Street West and Bay Street\, 
 or the western doors to the Atrium on Bay. The tour ends at old City Hall 
 on Queen Street West.\n\nAnd if you dare\, I'll see you soon on Toronto's 
 Darkest side.\n\nThis tour has a ticket price of $15.00 per person!\n\n\\*
 \\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket amount when booking your s
 pace for this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**[to
 rontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com/)**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/313004
 899/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260122T151934Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260122T151934Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_313413046@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260418T170000
SUMMARY:The Ward: Our First Immigrant Community and University Avenue!
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**[torontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gm
 ail.com/)**\n**for more information or for signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* *
 *Please note: Please e-transfer the ticket amount when booking your space 
 for this tour! You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**[toronto
 historywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com/)**\n\nThis i
 s an updated tour to the original Ward Tour introduced back in 2020. It br
 ings in a new crop of landmarks that tell the tale of Toronto's first subu
 rb Macaulaytown\, on the property of James Macaulay.\n\nThe Ward\, Toronto
 's first suburb\, first immigrant community and first large scale urban re
 newal project is a neighbourhood that dates to the beginnings of local his
 tory.\n\nBounded by Yonge Street on the east\, College Street on the north
 \, University on the West\, and Queen Street on the south\, is a history w
 alkers dream.\n\nBut before the area developed and a civic square was even
  dreamed of\, it was forest on the edge of Little York\, with a clear flow
 ing creek\, named Taddle at its centre. A few years later James Macaulay e
 stablished himself in the area northwest of the town of York.\n\nBy mid-ce
 ntury the winds of change brought in Chinese rail workers and Jewish immig
 rants\, mostly from Eastern Europe. The face of The Ward changed once agai
 n\, but this time the ugly realties of racial injustice were prominent.\n\
 nWith the building of the new Toronto General Hospital in 1909 the area re
 invented itself\, and the mass migration of jewish residents to the Kensin
 gton Market area to the west started. The Ward changed again and the idea 
 that the area could be a pedestrian square with a new town hall at its cen
 tre took shape. And the rest as they say is history\, Toronto got its new 
 civic square and Toronto a new voice at the dawn of a new era in city buil
 ding.\n\nThe ward is a fascinating look at life in Toronto in the late 19t
 h\, 20th\, and 21 century. For a quick preview of the walk click on the fo
 llowing link and enjoy https://youtu.be/4QEHjfuhmik\n\nThis walking tour i
 s for all walking levels and fitness skills. Please dress for the season a
 nd bring water. And remember to bring your love of history as well. Hope t
 o see you there.\n\nThis walking tour begins on the steps of Old City Hall
  at the northeast corner of Queen Street West\, and Bay Street. The tour r
 eturns to the start location at the Old City Hall.\n\nThis tour has a tick
 et price of $15.00 per person.\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer 
 the ticket amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfe
 r to the following email at:**\n**[torontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://t
 orontohistorywalks@gmail.com/)**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/313413
 046/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260218T143749Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260218T143749Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_313413102@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260419T110000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260419T130000
SUMMARY:Spring in Edwards Gardens and Historic Sunnybrook Park!
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or fo
 r signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the 
 following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nGet out and ex
 plore! A brilliant spring tour awaits\, and let's celebrate the coming sum
 mer.\n\nKnown as Sunnybrook Farm\, situated in Leaside\, it was owned by J
 oseph and Alice Kilgour and turned over to the City of Toronto in 1928 as 
 a public park.\n\nJoseph Kilgour was President of the Canada Paper Company
 . He and his wife purchased the property in the 1890s in the suburban frin
 ge.\n\nIn 1933\, Kilgour Memorial Gates and plaque at Wilket Creek Park we
 re added to honour the Kilgour family. The park is a quiet oasis in the he
 art of the city. But it's also about treasured Canadian history and our be
 loved Veterans who now call Sunnybrook Hospital home.\n\nThe Kilgour famil
 y gave the land for a hospital to be erected while the old veterans centre
  on Christie Street was literally falling apart. That's the way to treat t
 he Veterans who fought for our freedom\, put them in a cold\, wet hospital
  to recover\, way to go I must say!\n\nThis walking tour is for all walkin
 g levels and fitness skills\, however there are a few small hills. Please 
 dress for the season and bring water. And remember to bring your love of h
 istory as well. Hope to see you there.\n\nThis walking tour begins and end
 s at the main entrance of Edwards Gardens\, 755 Lawrence Ave East\, adjace
 nt to the Lawrence Avenue TTC bus stop and parking lot!\n\nThis tour has a
  ticket price of $15.00 per person!\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-tran
 sfer the ticket amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-tr
 ansfer to the following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/313413
 102/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260218T144226Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260218T144226Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_312865361@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T140000
SUMMARY:Teiaiagon\, Historic Jane Street\, and Baby Point
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n**The Toronto History Walks Yearly Pass
  is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\, emai
 l**\n[torontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com%
 2A%2A/)\n**for more information or for signing up!**\n\n**Please note: Ple
 ase e-transfer the ticket price when booking your space for this tour! You
  can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n[torontohistorywalks@gmail.c
 om](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com%2A%2A/)\n\nThe legendary village 
 of Teiaiagon\, and Baby Point are linked historically and traditionally. T
 he stories they have generated have been carried from one generation to th
 e next. The birth of Toronto itself swirled around the Longhouse encampmen
 t of this Seneca village years before British settlement.\n\nJames Baby wa
 s a member of an important French fur trading family and politician. He se
 ttled at Baby Point in 1816\, after discovering the ruins of the abandoned
  village on the property. An apple orchard covered the area and salmon was
  plentiful\, but trouble with the Baby family was proving disastrous to ou
 tsiders.\n\nJames Baby's family opposed John Graves Simcoe's effort to pro
 hibit slavery in Upper Canada.\n\nA fascinating tale and a fascinating nei
 ghbourhood. Many streets in this neighbourhood are named after this family
 .\n\nThis walk is for all walking levels and fitness skills. Please dress 
 for the season and bring water. And remember to bring your love of history
  as well. Hope to see you there.\n\nThis walking tour begins on the west s
 ide of Jane Street and Bloor Street West opposite the Jane Subway Station.
  We return to the starting point after the walk.\n\nThis tour has a ticket
  price of $15.00 per person!\n\n**Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t price when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the f
 ollowing email at:**\n[torontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistor
 ywalks@gmail.com%2A%2A/)
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/312865
 361/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260113T174343Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260113T174343Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_312865402@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260425T170000
SUMMARY:Tkaronto! And The Historic Carrying Place!
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n**The Toronto History Walks Yearly Pass
  is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\, emai
 l**\n[torontohistorywalks@gmail.com](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com%
 2A%2A/)\n**for more information or for signing up!**\n\n**Please note: Ple
 ase e-transfer the ticket price when booking your space for this tour! You
  can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n[torontohistorywalks@gmail.c
 om](http://torontohistorywalks@gmail.com%2A%2A/)\n\nThe Toronto Carrying P
 lace\, and the birth of Toronto are connected in many historic ways\, phys
 ically\, socially\, and spiritually as well! The historic path at one time
  connected the northern shore of Lake Ontario with the Great Lakes especia
 lly Lake Simcoe and Lake Huron\, and to the vast region known as Huronia\,
  or centred around Midland\, Ontario.\n\nThe entire area was known as Tkar
 onto\, from the old Mohawk term "where trees gathered in water."\n\nTeiaia
 gon\, the small Seneca village on the Humber River\, was named for the cro
 ssing of the Toronto Carrying Place\, and is now part of the Baby Point ne
 ighbourhood!\n\nOn this walk we explore the history of the Toronto Carryin
 g Place south from Bloor Street West to the mouth of the Humber River\, an
 d discuss the personalities who came to the area\, and travelled this very
  path from Jean Baptiste Rousseau\, the first French fur trader\, to Rober
 t La Salle the explorer of the mighty Mississippi River and many others.\n
 \nThis walk is for most walking levels and fitness skills with a few small
  hills. Please dress for the season and bring water. And remember to bring
  your love of history as well. Hope to see you there.\n\nThis walking tour
  begins on the west side of Jane Street and Bloor Street West opposite the
  Jane Subway Station. We end our journey at The Queensway and The South Ki
 ngsway which is adjacent to several TTC routes.\n\nThis tour has a ticket 
 price of $15.00 per person!\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the
  ticket amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer t
 o the following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/312865
 402/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260113T174910Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260113T174910Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_313175471@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260426T120000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260426T140000
SUMMARY:Hidden Wonders of Canada\; Northern Ontario History and Guide (LEC
 TURE ON THE GO)
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Explo
 rer Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tour
 s\, email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or 
 for signing up!\\*\\***\n\nWe have an amazing "Lecture on the Go" series f
 or 2026. New topics and fascinating stories abound! Join us and learn abou
 t the world and keep active and warm during the winter months!\n\nI starte
 d this walking classroom when we were under that horrible cloud called Cov
 id. This series was popular and helped people get out and back into societ
 y and life. The series is back for 2026 with 6 new topics for exploration 
 over the winter and spring months.\n\nThe "Lecture on the Go" Series is op
 en only to members who have purchased the YEARLY MEMBERSHIP PASS\, it's fr
 ee for those members. If you wish to attend a lecture and you are not a ye
 arly pass member then the price **per** lecture is $20.00.\n\nThis third l
 ecture is focussed on the History of Northern Ontario\, a place most don't
  know too much about\, and that's a shame. Northern Ontario is a place of 
 pure magic. Let's take a closer look at this fascinating subject.\n\nLong 
 before maps or borders\, or places like Cobalt or North Bay even appeared\
 , Indigenous peoples lived with the land\, traveling and followed the seas
 ons. Lakes were highways\, canoes were cars\, and everything you needed ca
 me from knowing the land. When Europeans showed up\, they didn’t so much
  “discover” the North as wander. Business was first to get a notice.\n
 \nCanoes loaded with beaver pelts\, trading posts popped up\, and suddenly
  Northern Ontario was connected to Europe. Things sped up fast once railwa
 ys arrived in the 1800s. Trains unlocked forests\, minerals\, and new town
 s were built. Places like Sudbury and Thunder Bay grew — nickel\, timber
 \, grain — and people followed jobs wherever they appeared. It was rugge
 d\, noisy\, and a little chaotic\, but it worked.\n\nToday\, Northern Onta
 rio is a world unto its own. Its big skies\, long drives\, and communities
  know how to adapt. The past is still there — in the land\, the towns\, 
 and the stories — but the North doesn’t dwell on it. It just keeps goi
 ng\, and it's up to us as Canadians to understand.\n\nTopics upcoming in t
 he 2026 series of lectures are as follows. We are a little behind but catc
 hing up.\n\n\\*Dante\; The Hidden Meaning Behind The Divine Comedy\n\\*Phi
 losophy 1: Great Minds of the Western World: Goethe to Kant!\n\\*Philosoph
 y 2: Great Minds of the Eastern World: Chuang Tzu to Dalai Lama\n\nHope to
  see you on this "Lecture on the Go!" So book your plans now!\n\nThis even
 t is for all levels and walkers\, there are a few steps here and there to 
 navigate\, but mostly on one level. This event in a non walking event.\n\n
 The lecture begins on the steps of Old City Hall at the northeast corner o
 f Bay Street and Queen Street West and head into the PATH.\n\nThis lecture
  event has a ticket price of $20.00 per person\, and is **free with the ye
 arly membership pass**. Hope to see you there!\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Pl
 ease e-transfer the ticket amount when booking your space for this tour! Y
 ou can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmai
 l.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/313175
 471/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260202T175400Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260202T175400Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_313413178@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260426T150000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260426T170000
SUMMARY:The Exhibition Grounds: History and Architecture (NEW FOR 2026)
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Explo
 rer Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tour
 s\, email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or 
 for signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the tic
 ket price when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the
  following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n\nThe beloved C
 NE started out as the Toronto Industrial Exhibition in 1879 and has been a
 n icon ever since.\n\nBut the history of the CNE dates back to the mid 180
 0s when the Provincial Agricultural Association set up the first exhibitio
 n in 1846 here in Toronto. The "Fair" was an Upper Canada fair and moved f
 rom one place to another for the first 30 years until the permanent exhibi
 tion was established in Toronto.\n\nSeen as a mini world's fair the Indust
 rial Exhibition changed the name in 1912 to the Canadian National Exhibiti
 on\, as was known as the "People's University."\n\nThe buildings were cons
 idered the most beautiful exhibition buildings on the continent. In 1906 t
 he Crystal Palace burned to the ground and the current horticultural build
 ing built on the site.\n\nThe architecture tells its own story of Toronto 
 and what Torontonians thought about their city. Pride in Toronto\, and all
  that it achieved was on display for all to see during the CNE days in lat
 e August.\n\nLearn about the history and the ups and downs of the "showpla
 ce of the nation."\n\nThis walk is for all walkers and all skill levels. P
 lease dress for the weather and bring water.\n\nPlease meet on the south s
 ide of Springhurst and Dufferin Street\, just north of the TTC loop.\n\nTh
 is tour has a ticket price of $15.00 per person.\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: 
 Please e-transfer the ticket price when booking your space for this tour! 
 You can e-transfer to the following email at:**\n**torontohistorywalks@gma
 il.com**
URL;VALUE=URI:https://www.meetup.com/the-history-of-parkdale/events/313413
 178/
STATUS:CONFIRMED
CREATED:20260218T144917Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260218T144917Z
CLASS:PUBLIC
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Meetup: History of Parkdale
UID:event_313412885@meetup.com
SEQUENCE:1
DTSTAMP:20260412T031511Z
DTSTART;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T113000
DTEND;TZID=America/Toronto:20260430T133000
SUMMARY:Mount Pleasant Cemetery (WEEKDAY)
DESCRIPTION:Toronto History Walks\n\\*\\***The Toronto History Walks Yearl
 y Pass is available. Get it now for $125.00 for 1 year of unlimited tours\
 , email**\n**torontohistorywalks@gmail.com**\n**for more information or fo
 r signing up!\\*\\***\n\n\\*\\* **Please note: Please e-transfer the ticke
 t amount when booking your space for this tour! You can e-transfer to the 
